result.execSummary:
The defendant Deangelo D Dunbar was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Deangelo D Dunbar in court with attorney Mary L. Roth Burns.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 1:42 PM. Burns - resolved - DRI counts #1 thru #4, plead to count #5 as alleged and to count #6 as alleged, withhold sentence and place on probation for 18 months, court costs, standard conditions of probation, AODA, no alcohol, counseling as deemed necessary by agent. State will ask for no contact with Tammy and Rosalind Mann. Burns did not talk about that condition. Defendant objects to the no contact with Tammy Mann for stated reasons. State will just ask for no contact with Rosalind Mann. State has complied with victim notification requirements with no response. Burns - agreement that if all fines and conditions are satisfied within the first 12 months of probation - early discharge from probation. State - leave up to Court the return of the weapon - may be mandatory possession. Court will make ruling on that at a different time if needed. Court has plea questionnaire. Dunbar pleads NC to count #5. State - needs to be a G plea. Recess to talk to defendant regarding a G plea (1:50 PM). Back on record at 1:50 PM. Dunbar will plead G to count #5 as alleged. Court makes sure defendant knows the difference between a NC or G plea. Dunbar asks question regarding possession of a weapon after probation is completed. Dunbar pleads G to counts #5 and #6 as alleged. Court dismisses and reads in counts #1 thru #4. Court goes thru plea questionnaire, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights by entering his plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation. Burns makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation. Court wants to hear from each side why there is no jail component of the sentencing. State responds - victims were not very cooperative. Burns responds and also informs Court that the defendant has 14 days of jail credit if revoked. State makes additional statement. Dunbar makes statement. Court sentences the defendant to the following: counts #5 and #6 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 18  months - concurrent to each other, with conditions of: costs on each count - take bond posted - refund remainder to poster, AODA and follow thru, submit DNA sample, counseling, any other conditions as deemed appropriate by P&P, no contact with Rosalind Mann, credit for 14 days only if revoked, Burns makes objection to DNA surcharge on each count, so noted, if all fees and supervision fees and conditions are met - no objection to early discharge after 12 months, Court makes no ruling on the return of the gun - Burns has 30 days to brief that matter, FOSO not to do anything with the weapon for at least 30 days, right to appeal.

Called 8:51 am. Judge Rhode appears telephonically from the bench in Langlade County. Charles Simono appears on behalf of the state. The defendant does not appear per leave of the court. Attorney Mary Burns appears in person on behalf of the defendant. Here on defense motion to compel discovery from the state. State indicates that he has supplied all discovery for stated reasons. Burns responds and gives examples of what she is looking from the discovery. State still believes that they have provided all discovery. Much discussion on the criminal witnesses that state is using. Court grants motion for stated reasons. Adjourned 8:59 am.
